item.title: Interactive graphs with plotly and ggvis
Predicting Blood Donations: Part 2
item.description:
Purpose

This post shows some basic modeling methods in R. Specifically, I model blood donation data with a linear and logit model. These models are well established an easy to inerpret. In a future post I’ll explore some more flexible models that might improve prediction.

Linear regression with lm

A linear model is the simplest and best understood method for modeling data, as well as a building block for more sophisticated methods. So I’ll start with it here, but note that it may not be appropriate for this data investigation since the outcome variable is a binary categorical variable.

The basic assumption is that the CEF is linear \[f(x) = \beta x\] In this context it is known as a linear probability model. The predicted value is thought of as the probability that \(y=1\). More precisely, it is supposed that there is a latent variable \(y^* = \beta x + \epsilon\) that determines the observed value of \(y = 1\{y^* > 0\}\). And we assume that \[\begin{eqnarray} E(y|x) &=& E(1\{y^* > 0\}|x) \\ &=& P(y^* > 0|x) \\ &=& P(\epsilon > -\beta x) \\ &=& 1 - F(-\beta x) = F(\beta x) = \beta x\end{eqnarray}\] This model may work well for some data points, but will violate the basic assumption for probabilities that \(0 \leq p \leq 1\) for some values of \(x\). To remedy this problem we can assume a different CDF, usually either \(F(x) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}\) or \(F(x) = \Phi(x)\), which lead to the logit and probit model respectively. For now, we’ll consider the linear model, \(F(x) = x\).

As mentioned in Part 1, we have to drop either number or volume because they are perfectly colinear. I’ve chosen to drop volume. The function for running linear regressions in R is lm from the stats package. lm returns an S3 object of class lm. Here’s how to use it:

donated_lm <- lm(donated07 ~ . - volume, data = training)

The results from running this regression can be obtained with accessor functions like coefficients and fitted.values, but to get a quick view use summary and anova

kable(xtable(summary(donated_lm)))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 0.3115899 0.0335642 9.283405 0.0000000
last -0.0094864 0.0022395 -4.235970 0.0000265
number 0.0221996 0.0040023 5.546738 0.0000000
first -0.0030232 0.0009528 -3.172856 0.0015905

Diagnostic checks

Potential problems with linear regression from Hastie et. al.

  1. Non-linearity of the response-predictor relationships
  2. Correlation of error terms
  3. Non-constant variance of error terms
  4. Outliers
  5. High-leverage points
  6. Collinearity

address each point

kable(vif(donated_lm), col.names = "vif") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = F)
vif
last 1.189356
number 1.872533
first 1.890806

Diagnostic information

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(donated_lm)

Really poor model.

Students, standards, and hats

studentize vs standarized, hatvalues function.

Heteroscedasticity library(sandwich) library(lmtest), summary(robust = T)

vc <- vcovHC(donated_lm, type="HC1")
coeftest(donated_lm, vcov = vc)
## 
## t test of coefficients:
## 
##                Estimate  Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.31158992  0.03708054  8.4031 3.457e-16 ***
## last        -0.00948641  0.00234600 -4.0436 5.984e-05 ***
## number       0.02219958  0.00423898  5.2370 2.297e-07 ***
## first       -0.00302320  0.00086672 -3.4881 0.0005239 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

One way we can reduce the dimension of this model is to creat a new variable that’s a function of the original variables. Lets consider the rate at which someone gives blood by dividing number by first. This new variable is the number of donations per Month. With only one regressor we can plot the regression model to get a better sense of how the model is fitting the data.

donated_nm_lm <- lm(donated07 ~ I(number/first), data = training)
summary(donated_nm_lm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = donated07 ~ I(number/first), data = training)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -0.7633 -0.2287 -0.1689 -0.1316  0.8649 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)      0.10947    0.02794   3.918 9.99e-05 ***
## I(number/first)  0.65383    0.11025   5.930 5.23e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.415 on 574 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.05773,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.05609 
## F-statistic: 35.17 on 1 and 574 DF,  p-value: 5.226e-09
plot(training$number/training$first, training$donated07)
abline(donated_nm_lm, lwd=3)

Doesn’t look too bad; this model dosn’t give any non-sensical results for any of the observations in our trianing set.

Logistic regression with glm

donated_glm <- glm(donated07 ~ . - volume, data = training, 
                   family = binomial)
summary(donated_glm)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = donated07 ~ . - volume, family = binomial, data = training)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.5102  -0.8079  -0.5273  -0.2427   2.5545  
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -0.585643   0.201818  -2.902  0.00371 ** 
## last        -0.091026   0.018955  -4.802 1.57e-06 ***
## number       0.129921   0.029102   4.464 8.03e-06 ***
## first       -0.018797   0.006588  -2.853  0.00433 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 634.29  on 575  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 556.61  on 572  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 564.61
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 5

Diagnostics

training <- mutate(training, nm = number/first)
donated_nm_glm <- glm(donated07 ~ nm, data = training, 
                          family = binomial)
summary(donated_nm_glm)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = donated07 ~ nm, family = binomial, data = training)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.7988  -0.7060  -0.6177  -0.5673   1.9449  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -1.8554     0.1711 -10.846  < 2e-16 ***
## nm            3.2522     0.6123   5.311 1.09e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 634.29  on 575  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 604.04  on 574  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 608.04
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4
grid <- data.frame(
  nm = seq(min(training$nm), max(training$nm), length.out = 1000))
plot(training$nm, training$donated07)
lines(grid$nm, predict(donated_nm_glm, 
                    newdata = grid, type = "response"))

Formal comparison of linear and logit. AIC

we’ve estmated several models. Let’s combine them with stargazer

Future post that estimates blood donation with more complex models. kNN, random forest, and neural network.

item.title: Innovation at Universities
item.description:
Who should have the rights to innovations created at a university: professors or the university? A natural answer would be the professors; they came up with the idea in the first place. But that’s not how it works in the US.

In the US, professors have rights to roughly a third of the income from patents and ventures started at universities. This arrangement is motivated by the fact that universities are a crucial partner in innovation. Universities supply the basic resources and environment needed to incubate risky ideas before it is clear they are viable commercial ventures. Those resources are costly. If universities aren’t compensated enough, they might not provide enough support for professors to bring their ideas to fruition.

In 1980 the US passed the Bayh-Dole Act with the hope that providing more compensation to universities would encourage more innovation. This eventually inspired several European countries to do the same. In 2003, Norway ended a policy known as “professor’s privilege” that gave professors full rights to new business ventures and intellectual property they created. Instead, Norway adopted a US-style policy that transferred two-thirds of these rights to the university. Economists Hans K. Hvide and Benjamin F. Jones observed the effects of this new US-style policy in their paper University Innovation and the Professor’s Privilege, published in the July 2018 issue of the AER.

Hvide and Jones found that not only did the policy fail to encourage innovation; both entrepreneurship and patenting rates by university researchers were cut in half after the reform. Furthermore, measures of quality for university start-ups and patents declined as well. While the authors perform a more detailed quantitative analysis in their paper, specifically a differences-in-differences regression model, you can still see a sharp contrast between university and non-university start-ups in the graph below.

Both university and non-university start-ups decline in 2003, the year that “professor’s privilege” ended, but the university start-up decline is sharper and fails to recover. Although not as dramatic of a difference as start-ups, the total number of university patents declines more sharply after 2003 than non-university patents.

The authors find this general pattern to hold under a number of different assumptions. To supplement their quantitative findings, they also conducted a survey of university inventors. The survey indicated that university inventors had a largely negative view of the reforms. Some respondents felt that the university’s ownership share did not reflect its contribution to commercializing an idea. To give a representative quote, one respondent said:

The university contributed little, but was entitled to a substantial income share.

You can see a summary of the respondents’ views of the reform in the table below. The authors caution that the response rate was only 22.3%.

Respondents Unknown Positive Negative
Effect on self 56 34 7 15
Effect on colleagues 56 42 4 10

Overall, the authors’ findings suggest that the investment that researchers put in to commercializing innovative ideas are more important than what universities bring to a new venture. But these findings are limited to Norway. Locating the right balance between a university’s interests and a researcher’s interests in order to encourage new technologies and companies is ultimately an empirical problem. Circumstances might vary widely from country to country or from university to university.

item.title: Measuring Measure for Measure
item.description:
Purpose

This is a work in progress, but I’d like to post a summary and my thoughts on Shakespeare’s Measure for Measure and then use it to perform some basic Natural Language Processing (NLP)

Note: if I end up doing a sentiment analysis, the sentiment libraries I’m aware of would not really be appropriate for early modern English.

Overview

Word Frequencies

Load Measure for Measure from the Gutenberg Project:

mm <- gutenberg_download(1126)

Tokenize

tidy_mm <- mm %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)

count

mm_count <- tidy_mm %>%
              count(word, sort = TRUE)
kable(head(mm_count)) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"))

item.title: Notes on The Elements of Statistical Learning
item.description:
• Purpose
  • The Bias-Variance Tradeoff
    • Note: Statistics vs Econometrics
  • Tree-based Methods

Purpose

The Elements of Statistical Learning by Hastie et. al. is the best resource I’ve found for understanding modern statistical and machine learning techniques. These techniques aim to answer problems of the following kind: what’s the best approximation to the conditional expectation function \(f(x) = E[Y|X]\)? Or more generally, what is our best guess for \(Y\) given what we know about \(X\)? Where ‘best’ can be defined in a number of ways, but usually results in trying to approximate the conditional expectation function (CEF). A critical assumption made in most of these techniques is that the error is additive, so that the general model is \[ Y = f(x) + \epsilon\] along with some assumptions about how \(\epsilon\) is distributed. The assumptions on \(\epsilon\) should not be considered an after thought; often they are the most important part of the model, especially when you’re interested in causal questions (see Mostly Harmless Econometrics).

I want to summarize and replicate some of the results from their book (as well as from their introductory book An Introduction to Statistical Learning) to get a better handle on these techniques.

The Bias-Variance Tradeoff

A theme running throughout The Elements of Statistical Learning is that any estimation strategy must make a choice between how much bias or variance to tolerate. Hastie et. al. have a nice discussion of this in their overview chapter. They note that the mean squared error of an estimator is \[MSE(\hat{f}(x)) = Var(\hat{f}(x))+ [Bias(\hat{f}(x))]^2 + Var(\epsilon)\] The variance of \(\epsilon\) is the irreducible error. There’s nothing that our model can do to reduce this error. The bias and variance of \(\hat{f}(x)\) can however be reduced. Roughly, the bias results from misspecifying the CEF and the variance of \(\hat{f}(x)\) is due to sampling error, which can be reduced by increasing the sample size. So it would seem obvious that we should choose correctly specified models to get the best predictions, but what Hastie et. al. show is that often times we can do better by intentionally biasing our model if the variance is reduced enough in exchange.

Note: Statistics vs Econometrics

Econometrics places a lot of emphasis on obtaining unbiased and consitent estimators (see Introduction to Econometrics by Stock and Watson). That doesn’t seem to be the case in statistics. I think this is due to different interests: prediction vs causality. It’s certainly more common to hear econometricians say they are more interested in causality. In the linear regression model \[y = \beta x + \epsilon\] an economist wants the best guess for \(\beta\), which would tell us what \(y\) would be if we changed \(x\). More generally, an economist want the best guess for \(f(x+\delta)-f(x)\). In contrast, a statistician wants the best guess for \(y\). Although, the distinction doesn’t seem that significant. Maybe a better way of describing the difference is to say that economists care more about what we don’t know, i.e. what’s in the error term.

Tree-based Methods

The tree method is very intuitive. We would like to approximate a function \(f(x)\) by partitioning its domain and approximating the function over each region with a constant equal to the average value of \(y\) in each region. Deciding how to partition the domain results in different trees.

item.title: Predicting Blood Donations: Part 1
item.description:
Purpose

This post shows some basic R usage, data cleaning and exploration, and visualization methods. In Part 2, I explore some quantitative methods.

Obtaining data in R

R has a useful function called download.file, which I show here for future reference. Using the option method = curl, and maybe the extra option to pass additional arguments, I can download data from the DrivenData website.

training_data_url <- "https://s3.amazonaws.com/drivendata/data/2/public/
                      9db113a1-cdbe-4b1c-98c2-11590f124dd8.csv"
train_file <- "../../data/training.csv"
if(!file.exists(train_file)){
  download.file(training_data_url, train_file, method = "curl")
}

test_data_url <- "https://s3.amazonaws.com/drivendata/data/2/public/
                  5c9fa979-5a84-45d6-93b9-543d1a0efc41.csv"
test_file <- "../../data/test.csv"
if(!file.exists(test_file)){
  download.file(test_data_url, test_file, method = "curl")
}

This is pretty small data set with only 5 variable: 4 independent variables and 1 binary dependent variable.

training <- read.csv("../../data/training.csv", row.names = 1)
kable(data.frame(Names = c("last", "number", "volume", "first", "donated07"),
                 Description = names(training))) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"))
Names Description
last Months.since.Last.Donation
number Number.of.Donations
volume Total.Volume.Donated..c.c..
first Months.since.First.Donation
donated07 Made.Donation.in.March.2007

Next, to look at the first few rows of data, I run:

names(training) <- c("last", "number", "volume", "first", "donated07")
kable(head(training)) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"))
last number volume first donated07
619 2 50 12500 98 1
664 0 13 3250 28 1
441 1 16 4000 35 1
160 2 20 5000 45 1
358 1 24 6000 77 0
335 4 4 1000 4 0

read.csv vs read_csv

I chose to use read.csv here since this data set came with row names. But in general, read_csv loads data faster and reads the data into a tibble, and tibbles do not have row names.read.csv reads the data into a data.frame.

Exploring the data in R

First lets check the summary statistics and correlations with outcome variable:

cor_row <- c("Corr.", round(cor(training$donated07, training), 4))
training %>%
  summary() %>%
  tidy() %>%
  mutate(Freq = as.character(Freq)) %>%
  separate(Freq, c("statistic", "value"), ":") %>%
  select(-one_of("Var1")) %>%
  rename(variable = Var2) %>%
  spread(variable, value) %>%
  rbind(cor_row) %>%
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"))
statistic last number volume first donated07
1st Qu. 2.000 2.000 500 16.00 0.0000
3rd Qu. 14.000 7.000 1750 49.25 0.0000
Max. 74.000 50.000 12500 98.00 1.0000
Mean 9.439 5.427 1357 34.05 0.2396
Median 7.000 4.000 1000 28.00 0.0000
Min. 0.000 1.000 250 2.00 0.0000
Corr. -0.2612 0.2206 0.2206 -0.0198 1

Next, let’s graph the histograms and scatter plots of the co-variates. A quick way to do this is to plot a scatter matrix. I’ll color by the outcome variable donated07.

ggpairs(training, aes(colour=factor(donated07)), 
        diag = list(continuous = wrap('barDiag', bins = 20)),
        columns = 1:(ncol(training)-1), progress = F)

Notice that number and volume are perfectly correlated, which means that one of them needs to be dropped in any regression. The remaining co-variates do not look strongly correlated. It also looks like first might be top-coded at 100 months.

People who were more likely to donate in 2007 seemed to donate more in general, either by frequency or volume. Their last donation also seemed to be more recent. The scatter matrix doesn’t reveal much else to my eye. In part 2, I’ll consider quantitative methods to estimate the strength of these qualitative observations.

Note: data pre-processing

To remove duplicate rows, we can use the unique or distinct functions. unique returns all the unique rows of a data frame. distinct is an optimized version of unique from the dplyr package. distnct can also drop duplicate values based on any number of columns. Or to return the duplicated rows we could use duplicated:

training[duplicated(training), ]

It’s easy to forget that row names aren’t considered when checking for duplicates. So, in this case, we would want to include an id column and then remove any duplcates. This is also a point in favor of using tibbles.

Removing missing values is simple in R too. We can use complete.cases or na.omit. na.omit returns a data frame without any rows containing NA. And complete.cases returns the indices of rows without NA, so it can be used to return rows with NA:

training[!complete.cases(training),]
## [1] last      number    volume    first     donated07
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

Clearly, the training data set in this example doesn’t contain any missing values.

Finally, it’s a good idea to check for any impossible values. Writing a custom function for a data set is a good way to document any changes you’ve made. For example, we know that every variable in this data set must be non-negative and first >= last. So we could write the following function to remove any rows that violate these conditions:

clean <- function(x) {
  if (!is.data.frame(x)) stop('x must be a data.frame.')
  x_cleaned <- x %>%
    filter(first >= last) %>%
    filter_all(any_vars(. >= 0))
  return(x_cleaned)
}
training_cleaned <- clean(training)
sum(!training_cleaned==training)
## [1] 0

We can see that all of the observations satisfy the conditions we put in clean.
